# Facets of this nexus — use them, they exist for you

The `.work` format and this runtime carry facets beyond prose. Not using them is
losing information.

## Issues (the request lane)

Any run — yours or a limb's — that hits an error, a missing tool, or an
architectural limitation FILES it and continues: `request self '<typed change>'`.
Fire-and-forget; the autopoet senses it next heartbeat. Complaints written into
answer prose instead of filed are lost. Failed limb runs auto-file.

## Todos ([[todos]])

Open work lives in the todos page as dated org-timestamp entries. Append new
entries; append completion lines when done; never rewrite history. The todos page
is how work survives between heartbeats and how anyone — human or autopoet —
knows where things left off.

## Hash notes (ephemeral notes that become memories)

Inline notes with a polarity marker at line start:

+# a PINNED note — stays at its anchor in the source, always visible.
-# a DRAWER note — ephemeral by design: a sweep collapses it out of the source
   into the drawer (a queryable HashNote row) and commits it to git; a `≡<hash>`
   handle remains at the anchor. `git show <hash>` recovers it forever.

Use `-#` for working thoughts you want remembered but not cluttering; `+#` for
notes the next reader must see.

## History (your own)

Your prompts carry your recent knowledge lessons and the human gate's verdicts on
your recent proposals (with reasons when given). Read them before proposing —
repeating a rejected shape wastes a round.

## Limits do not exist

No turn limits, no work-bounding clocks — only a distant fail-mode ceiling.
Hooks and the log communicate progress; nothing interrupts work. Close when done.
